ntent-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230826_PDP504.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><style data-emotion="css 18w36g1">.css-18w36g1{width:100%;font-family:var(--ds-type-system-sans);}</style><figcaption class="css-18w36g1 e16qazw92"><style data-emotion="css 11jvxbd">.css-11jvxbd{font-family:var(--ds-type-system-sans-smallcaps);font-size:var(--ds-type-scale--1);font-weight:400;font-variant-ligatures:none;line-height:var(--ds-type-leading-lower);text-transform:lowercase;color:var(--ds-color-london-35);}.e16qazw90+.css-11jvxbd{margin-left:0.5rem;}</style><span class="css-11jvxbd e16qazw91">图片：阿拉米</span></figcaption></figure></section><p data-caps="initial" class="article__body-text article__body-text--dropcap"><span data-caps="initial">虽然</span>有些人喜欢学习数学，但这个学科却困扰着许多孩子整个学校及以后的生活。但事实并非一定如此。数学家、《数学是真实的吗？》一书的作者尤金妮亚·程 (Eugenia Cheng) 解释了为什么对她来说，数学是一项令人快乐的事业。在接受《经济学人》科技编辑阿洛克·贾 (Alok Jha) 的采访中，尤金妮亚 (Eugenia) 探讨了如何通过提出看似简单的问题来揭开数字背后的深层奥秘。她还认为，教育系统应该重新思考该学科的教学方式，以鼓励好奇心和创造力。时长：34分钟</p><p class="article__body-text"><iframe height="21